******
[2]
Date: Thu 8 Nov 2007
Source: Xinhua [edited]
<http://english.people.com.cn/90001/90782/6298854.html>


The Cypriot government on Wednesday [7 Nov 2007] approved measures to
support stockbreeders who have been affected by the outbreak of FMD.

"Tackling this problem needs strict measures. We all understand the
sorrow and devastation of the affected stockbreeders, whose livestock
will have to be killed. The problem we face is serious, but the
government will support the animal breeders," said the President
after a cabinet meeting.

The European Commission has labeled Cyprus as a "high risk zone" and
banned the export of Cypriot meat following the FMD outbreak in the
southern Larnaca District. But the ban does not include the famous
Cypriot cheese, halloumi.

European Union experts said that all data collected so far indicates
that the type O virus led to the FMD outbreak in Cyprus. Hundreds of
sheep and goats have been culled so far.

--
Communicated by:
FMD News
FMD Surveillance and Modeling Laboratory
University of California at Davis
<fmdweb@ucdavis.edu>

[The event in Cyprus is rather enigmatic. As it appears from the
official OIE notification and from the media, the declaration of an
"outbreak" is based upon serological evidence only. It is not clear
where and when the sheep underwent seroconversion, becoming positive
to FMD virus O.

Other susceptible animals on the same or adjacent premises,
particularly cattle, should be tested as well. If found serologically
negative to FMD, the origin of the positive sheep should be subject
to a thorough investigation. The exclusion of local infection with
FMD may be supported by testing the bovines for bluetongue; if
positive results are obtained, this will strongly indicate that
bluetongue was indeed responsible for the clinical signs observed in
the Dromolaxia sheep during the 2nd half of October 2007. - Mod.AS]
